Fix the undo function to propogate through adding pieces.
chess-python clears the move stack if you overwrite a square.
it does support "drop" moves like in Crazyhouse, but I want to support changing a piece too.
So let's not try and use the official stack?

Ability to set title and subtext? Nah, no need.

new moves field for Fenlist. a1e5 UCi format with additional 'reset' and 'checkpoint' setting and returning keywords. then use arrow keys to navigate. could preparse into a tree of fens
1) Add Moves: field to FEN_LIST loader.
2) Allowed syntax are:
    + a1b2 style moves, including a7a8Q, already in UCI format;
    + add checkpoint, to return here later
    + return to home
    + return to (saved) checkpoint
    + "add a piece" to a particular square;
    + "remove a piece" from a particular square
    + "changing a piece" on a particular square # not needed, can just add over the top


assume MoveToHome is signified by "H" this will involve appending the Home Fen, and updating the checkpoint index

assume SetBranchPoint/SaveCheckpoint is signified by "*" this triggers adding a word to the fen list later, but not appending a FEN itself
option is to always add a fen but then later remove adjacent duplicates

move to checkpoint will involve adding a fen to the list (which will be a repeat)

we might as well keep track of all checkpoints, but we will never need to return to future ones
so it makes sense to create our list of fens, and we use << <<< and < to determine how many back in our checkpoints list we move

* = add checkpoint here
< = back to last/current checkpoint
<< = back 2 checkpoints
H = go home (checkpoint 0)

samplemoves = ["e2e4", "e7e5", "g1f3", "b8c6", "*", "f1b5", "a7a6", "<", "f1c4" "f8c5", "*", "b2b4", "c5b4", "<", "c2c3", "d7d5", "<<", "d2d4", "e5d4", "H", "g1f3", "g7g5", "f3g5"]

change Config __init__ function into a startup(cls) function, then don't need to call config = Config(), save __init__ for when you really want an instance. __init__(self) can just run self.startup()

Consider a separate config for tk window and for pygame. What config values does tk even want to know? We currently now run config AFTER spawning the pygame (for multiprocessing spawn Windows rules)
